                <affiliation>The Century</affiliation>
                <note>Richard Watson Gilder was a poet and editor of the Century magazine. Нe worked as a reporter for the <hi rend="italic">Newark Daily Advertiser</hi> and the <hi rend="italics">Newark Morning Register</hi> before becoming editor of the magazine <hi rend="italic">Hours At Home</hi> in 1869. When the latter was merged with the newly-founded <hi rend="italic">Scribner's Monthly</hi> the following year, Gilder was made assistant editor under Josiah Gilbert Holland. Не succeeded Holland as editor-in-chief in 1881 and turned the publication, renamed <hi rend="italic">The Century Illustrated Monthly Magazine</hi>, into the most renowned and influential general interest magazine in the United States ("Overview," <hi rend="italic">Richard Watson Gilder papers, 1855-1916</hi> Manuscripts and Archives Division, The New York Public Library, 1987: 1).</note>
            </person>   
        </listPerson>
        
        
        <listObject>
